<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="121" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,416,1017]" pageId="20" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,488,513]" pageId="20" pageNumber="121">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be separated from other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1054,490,513]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Semanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[933,1054,490,513]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="121">Semanotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: color dark brown to black; elytra pale yellow except for black maculation in the form of one pair of medium sized spots and apical 
<number box="[514,524,561,585]" pageId="20" pageNumber="121" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[535,549,561,585]" pageId="20" pageNumber="121" value="3.0">3</number>
of elytra, rarely with spots enlarged basally to form an oblong ‘tongue-like’ longitudinal band; mandible without median tooth; elytral punctation and pubescence distinct: pale setae restricted to pale areas where the punctation is larger and more widely separated, and dark setae restricted to dark areas where the punctation is smaller, and almost contiguous (in the rare case when the basal area of the elytra is dark, the pubescence remains pale), pubescence semi-erect to decumbent; elytra with erect setae along suture usually only in basal ½; ventral pubescence white to grey, semi-erect to decumbent, fine, sparse, surface of ventrites not obscured.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,416,1017]" box="[199,1092,777,802]" pageId="20" pageNumber="121">
